# No Silent Data Exclusions

## ZERO DISCRETION POLICY

Never decide on your own to exclude a field, element, column, schedule section,
or any other piece of data from a parser, entity, query, or display.

Every exclusion requires explicit user approval before implementation.

## Required behavior

When recon reveals data that could be captured, present the full inventory to
the user and ask which items to include or exclude. Do not pre-filter it.

Before writing any code that omits a field that exists in the source data:

1. List the field and explain what it contains.
2. Ask the user whether to include or exclude it.
3. Wait for an explicit answer.

## Prohibited judgement calls

- "This field is a compliance flag — not analytically useful." — No. Ask.
- "This is a rolling average — complex to model." — No. Ask.
- "This only applies to a small subset of orgs." — No. Ask.
- "The total already covers this detail." — No. Ask.
- "I'll skip the multi-year averages for now." — No. Ask.
- Presenting a design summary that omits fields without disclosing the omission. — No.
  Always disclose what you are proposing to exclude before the user approves the design.

## Scope

Applies to all data ingestion work: XML parsers, scrapers, database queries,
API clients, CSV importers, and any other source-to-domain mapping.
